{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511159"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:38:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:38:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11706"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11706"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.09,0.02,0.06,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107806"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4321"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11706"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90236"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"1821"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"3382"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5885"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6356"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26962"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44587"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44712"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107806"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of severe epigastric pain radiating to his back. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He drinks approximately 60 units of alcohol per week. On examination, he appears unwell with pulse rate 110/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 32/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is tender in the epigastrium with guarding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin 145 g/L (130-170)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count 18.2 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelet count 320 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESerum lipase 890 U/L (10-140)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is managed with intravenous fluids and analgesia. He makes a good early response to treatment, but after 24 hours he develops tachypnoea and has an obvious increased effort in breathing. His SpO2 is now 85% on room air.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurther investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EArterial blood gases (room air): PaO2 50 mmHg (80-100), PaCO2 36 mmHg (35-45), pH 7.29 (7.36-7.44)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EChest X-ray: bilateral pulmonary infiltrates (Image)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cardiogenic pulmonary oedema","Pulmonary haemorrhage","Pulmonary contusion","Hospital acquired pneumonia","Acute respiratory distress syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient was admitted with acute pancreatitis and then became acutely unwell, with tachypnoea and hypoxaemia. Together with the bilateral pulmonary infiltrates seen on the chest X-ray, this fits with a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute respiratory distress syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. ARDS is a recognised complication of acute pancreatitis and is characterised by the 2012 Berlin definition: \u0022\u003Cem\u003EARDS is an acute diffuse, inflammatory lung injury, leading to increased pulmonary vascular permeability, increased lung weight, and loss of aerated lung tissue\u2026[with] hypoxaemia and bilateral radiographic opacities, associated with increased venous admixture, increased physiological dead space and decreased lung compliance.\u003C/em\u003E\u0022\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiogenic pulmonary oedema\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of acute dyspnoea and bilateral pulmonary infiltrates. However, it is less likely in this patient given the absence of cardiac history, normal heart size on chest X-ray, and the clinical context of acute pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E can present with acute dyspnoea, hypoxaemia and bilateral infiltrates. However, it typically presents with haemoptysis and is associated with conditions such as vasculitis, coagulopathy or severe thrombocytopenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHospital-acquired pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E is a clinical diagnosis with imaging suggestive of pneumonia. Signs of pneumonia on a chest radiograph include airspace opacification, consolidation of the affected area, and air bronchograms. Consolidation and air bronchograms are not present on this radiograph.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary contusion\u003C/strong\u003E typically results from blunt chest trauma and presents with patchy infiltrates on imaging. The absence of trauma history and the clinical context of acute pancreatitis make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["ARDS diagnosis is based on acute onset hypoxaemia with bilateral pulmonary infiltrates in the absence of cardiac failure.","Acute pancreatitis can lead to systemic complications including ARDS due to release of inflammatory mediators.","The Berlin criteria for ARDS require PaO2/FiO2 ratio \u003C300 mmHg with bilateral opacities not fully explained by effusions, collapse or nodules."],"references":["Thompson BT, Chambers RC, Liu KD. Acute Respiratory Distress Syndrome. N Engl J Med. 2017 Aug 10;377(6):562-572. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra1608077. PMID: 28792873. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28792873/","Diamond M, Peniston HL, Sanghavi DK, et al. Acute Respiratory Distress Syndrome. [Updated 2024 Jan 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK436002/","Matthay MA, Zemans RL, Zimmerman GA, Arabi YM, Beitler JR, Mercat A, Herridge M, Randolph AG, Calfee CS. Acute respiratory distress syndrome. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2019 Mar 14;5(1):18. doi: 10.1038/s41572-019-0069-0. PMID: 30872586; PMCID: PMC6709677. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30872586/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90236"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11706"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20112"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20112"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/257fba97-3f8d-492d-a59d-0feab0c627d1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/257fba97-3f8d-492d-a59d-0feab0c627d1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":762,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90236"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-